Package org.neo4j.cursor

Interface RawCursor<T,​EXCEPTION extends Exception>

  • All Superinterfaces:
    AutoCloseable, Supplier<T>
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    Cursor<T>, IOCursor<T>, TransactionCursor
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    EagerlyReversedTransactionCursor, EmptyIOCursor, LogEntryCursor, PhysicalTransactionCursor, ReversedMultiFileTransactionCursor, ReversedSingleFileTransactionCursor
    public interface RawCursor<T,​EXCEPTION extends Exception>
extends Supplier<T>, AutoCloseable
    A cursor is an object that moves to point to different locations in a data structure. The abstraction originally comes from mechanical slide rules, which have a "cursor" which slides to point to different positions on the ruler.

    Each position a cursor points to is referred to as a "row".

    Access to the current row is done by subtyping this interface and adding accessor methods. If no call to next() has been done, or if it returned false, then such accessor methods throw IllegalStateException.
